# Docker Day_1 Notes

# 🐳 Docker Notes

## 1. What is Docker?

Docker is an **open-source containerization platform** that allows developers to build, package, distribute, and run applications in isolated environments called **containers**.

Docker ensures that an application runs the same way on every machine by packaging the application together with all its required dependencies.

### Why Docker?

Without Docker:

* Applications may work on one system but fail on another.
* Different library versions can create compatibility issues.
* Setting up environments can be time-consuming.

With Docker:

* Applications run consistently.
* Deployment is faster.
* Collaboration becomes easier.
* Development and production environments remain the same.

---

# 2. What is a Docker Image?

A **Docker Image** is a **read-only template** used to create Docker containers.

It contains everything required to run an application:

* Application code
* Runtime
* Libraries
* Dependencies
* System tools
* Configuration files

Think of an image as a blueprint or recipe.

One image can create multiple containers.

---

# 3. What is a Docker Container?

A **Docker Container** is the **running instance of a Docker image**.

When an image is executed, Docker creates a container.

A container is:

* Lightweight
* Portable
* Isolated
* Fast
* Temporary (unless data is stored externally)

---

# 4. Docker Image vs Docker Container

| Docker Image                    | Docker Container                           |
| ------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| Blueprint                       | Running application                        |
| Read-only                       | Read and write                             |
| Used to create containers       | Created from images                        |
| Stored locally or on Docker Hub | Runs on the Docker Engine                  |
| Can create many containers      | Exists only while running (unless stopped) |

### Real-life Example

Imagine baking a cake.

* **Recipe** = Docker Image
* **Cake** = Docker Container

One recipe can be used to bake many cakes.

---

# 5. Why is Docker Efficient?

Docker is efficient because:

* Containers share the host operating system.
* No separate operating system is required for each application.
* Applications start within seconds.
* Less memory is used.
* CPU utilization is lower.
* Faster deployment.
* Better scalability.

---

# 6. Containers Include Dependencies

One major advantage of Docker is that containers package:

* Application code
* Libraries
* Runtime
* Dependencies
* Configuration files

This eliminates the famous problem:

> "It works on my machine."

The application behaves the same everywhere.

---

# 7. Isolation

Docker containers are isolated from one another.

Each container has its own:

* File system
* Processes
* Network
* Environment variables
* Installed software

Problems inside one container generally do not affect other containers.

---

# 8. Linux Namespaces

Docker achieves isolation using **Linux Namespaces**.

A namespace separates system resources so each container believes it has its own environment.

Different containers cannot directly access each other's resources.

---

# Types of Namespaces

## PID Namespace

* Isolates processes.
* Each container has its own process IDs.

---

## Network Namespace

Provides:

* Own IP address
* Network interfaces
* Routing table
* Ports

---

## Mount Namespace

Provides an independent filesystem.

Containers cannot see files outside their assigned filesystem.

---

## UTS Namespace

Allows each container to have its own:

* Hostname
* Domain name

---

## IPC Namespace

Isolates communication mechanisms such as:

* Shared memory
* Message queues
* Semaphores

---

## User Namespace

Maps users inside the container to different users on the host.

Improves security.

---

# 9. Linux Control Groups (cgroups)

Docker uses **Control Groups (cgroups)** to limit and monitor resource usage.

They prevent one container from consuming all system resources.

---

# Types of cgroups

## CPU

Limits processor usage.

---

## Memory

Limits RAM usage.

---

## Block I/O

Controls disk read/write speed.

---

## Network

Limits network bandwidth.

---

## Devices

Controls access to hardware devices.

---

## Freezer

Temporarily pauses and resumes containers.

---

# 10. Trusted Images

Always use trusted Docker images.

Trusted images are:

* Official images
* Verified publishers
* Frequently updated
* Secure
* Well maintained

Examples:

* ubuntu
* python
* nginx
* mysql
* redis

Avoid downloading unknown or unverified images.

